{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_carmichael_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657529/1924050101/0442.xml":{"full_text":"arsenal, and the photograph was taken upon its arrival at the Watertown arsenal, where it will be fitted with a carriage.* The gun, which\nrWfr-y? jp\u00a3p% 1 HHQfIHHHHrapj\nweighs 320 tons without n carriage, will be placed to command the entrance of Boston harbor. By United News Pictures.\n>l' WORLD\u2019S RICHEST BABY IS CHRISTENED. TLe daughter of Lord the General Electric Company, Lynn, Mass., yesterday, a ray of light\n/4\\ and Lady Mountbatten was recently christened at the Chapel Royal, was made to turn corners, loop-the-loop, and do other stunt-. A nw-\nSavoy, England, receiving the name of Patricia Edwina. The Prince terial known as fused quartz, the most transparent man ha\nmanage- to land a good -hare of the prizes. The girl- who win place- in the senior boat come from all over the I nited States.\nJ inMhe *w o7l'd ni \u00b0M i^ P I |ic this country repre-entatives on the reparation- commi--ion. \\'bo returned recently from\n\u201cnumber t l\nwMi \\'W i smJi: m m HrJ *^iMi^im\u2014\u2014\u2014^ z~ lih|9B\u00dfF'|^\nONSIDERING IIH 'A ORi.D COl R I \\ND \\MERII \\N PARTICIPATION. Suhcommiltec of the foreign relations coiunutife of the Senate, in\np CARDINAL HAYES CELEBRATES FIRST PONTIFICAL MASS. Photograph taken at St. Patrick\u2019s Cathedral, New York, yesterday. Cardinal session yesterday. Left to right: Senators Pittman, Swanson, Pepper, Brandegee and ShipsteadL At right (those who testified): James G.\nHayes is surrounded by archbishops and bishops, the procession passing into the church. Copyright by Cnderwood i fndonvood McDonald, Walker D. Hines, Arthur E. Hungerford, Bishop Charles H. Brent and George W. W Lckersham. National Photo.\nURGE AVAILABILITY\nOF DISTRICT FUND\nRhode Island Avenue Citizens\nWant Surplus for D. C.\nNeeds.\n$4,500,000 IN TREASURY\nAssociation Also Indorses Capper\nSchool Census Bill.\nMoney now in the Treasury which\nCongress has held to he the property\nof the District should be placed to\nthe credit of the District and used\nfor needed improvements, such as\nschools, salary increases and other\nbenefits, according to a resolution\nadopted last night by the Rhode\nIsland Avenue Citizens\u2019 Association,\nmeeting at the Sherwood Presby\nterian Church. Noah J. Brumbaugh,\nauthor of the resolution, pointed out\nthat about $1,500,000 now lies un\nexpended in the Treasury out of un\nappropriated District revenues and\nthat additional revenue will be gained\nby imposition of the gasoline tax,\nwhich will probably also swell the\n.fund in the Treasury. The resolution\nwas presented by ,T. P. Benfer, chair\nman of the committee on legislation\nof the association.\nNotwithstanding that the District\nfire marshal recommended changes\nt-lh construction of the Bangdon School\nflo avoid fire risks, nothing has been\ndone about the matter and some ac\ntion should be taken immediately,\nthe chairman of the school\u2019committee\nreported. The school committee also\nurged passage of the Capper bill pro\nviding for a school census, which was\nindorsed by the association.\nA large pond at 17th street and\nRhode Island avenue northeast,\ncaused by accumulation of water in a\ncut, menaces the lives of children and\neven adults, .1. F. Me Beth declared.\nThe association in a resolution in\ntroduced by \\V. S. Torbert again went\non record in opposition to the use of\nthe one-man street car on Rhode\nIsland avenue, and requested the\nPublic Ptilities Commission to place\nits ban on the use of these cars. The\nresolution also instructed the com\nmittee on legislation to draw\" up and\nintroduce in Congress a bill compell\ning the use of a full crew of two men\non street cars in the District of Co\nlumbia.\nConstruction of a road from the\nend of Rhode Island avenue to Hyatts\nvilio was urg.-d in a resolution passed\nby th.e association. C. R Engel led\na group of the members in a com\nmunity sing preceding the meeting.\nThe following candidates were elect\ned to membership:\nCharles H. Cook. Fred C. Christ, S.\nF. Grant, Ranay Passeno, Robert O.\nJennings. E. S. Moorhead, jr\u201e Wil\nliam I* Nesbitt, William W. Beard,\nRaymond W. Murphy, Anton F. Snie\ngoski. Anna M. Santmyer, George W.\nWeudal. K. Ij. Santm; r. John H.\nKeller, E. .1. Worthy, Wi'.bur I'. Finch,\nW. S. Tyler. Herman H. Moyer, Mrs.\nRuby Edmonds, Charles H. Caldwell,\njr.. Carl E. Duehring, Leon M. Thomp\nson, George F. Komer, N. R Terry,\n.Raul M. Tebault, Truman F. Henning,\n:K. F. Scott, Neal D. Bragaw, J. H.\nUlousor. George G. Culberton, James\nJB. Robinson, A B. Mustain, Douglas\njO. Reed, John A, Robb, G TL Ivins,\nJulia H, Underwood, Robert B. Doing,\nB. R Moyer, A. S .MacLachlan, W. B.\nprndorff, J. Engelberg. O. V. Kessler\nJ ind E. W. Hobina\nMay Day Joyously Observed in D. C.\nAt Playgrounds and Social Centers\nChildren Dance in Ancient Pole Ceremony and Fes\ntivals\u2014Pageants Given at Neighborhood\nHouses\u2014Athletic Events Featured.\nWashington, in conjunction with\nthe celebrations held in practically\nj every city in the world, today ob-\nI served the advent of May. Wherever\nthere is a playground or wherever\nj children can be gathered the ancient\ni festivals and crowning of the May\nj queen, which dates back to the early\nI Romans, will be observed,\nj A \u201cSong Festival\u201d will be held to\ni day, tomorrow and Saturday at the\nj Neighborhood House, 470 N street\nsouthwest, from 4 p.m. until 10 p.m.\nThis celebration will be for the bene\nfit of the house, which needs money\nto carry on its summer work. Be\nsides the program in which the vari\nous clubs of the Neighborhood House\ntake part, a supper will be served\nevery day from 5 p.m. to 7 p.m.\nMaypole Dance Today.\nToday and tomorrow there will be\na,Maypole dance in the evening at 8\no\u2019clock. On all, three days \u201cThe Change\nling.'' a fairy play, will be pre\nsented. On Saturday at 5 p.m. there\nwill be a \u201cSpring Procession,\" the\ncrowning of the Queen of the May,\nfairy dances. Maypole dances and\nspring song dances.\nThe girls to take part at Plaza play-\ngrounds have been trained by Mrs.\nCatherine Swanson, director of rec\nreation at the Plaza, which is under\n|the jurisdiction of the playground de\npartment. The boys\u2019 athletics are un\n-1 der the supervision of Richard Ten\nnyson, and similar activities for the\ngirls are directed by Miss Maude Par\nker.\ni Commissioner Oyster and Mrs. Susie\ni Root Rhodes, supervisor of play\ngrounds, will be among the guests to\nbe present at the party.\nCeremonies at Plus.\nThe Plaza party will begin with ath\njletics by the boys while the Marine\nBand is playing. Next, the corona\ntion of the May queen, Letheia Kee-\nI see of Peabody School. Those wbo\ntake part in the Maypole dance are;\nGertrude Spigone, Eleanor Kennedy,\nEloise Gerard, Elizabeth May, Sallie\nWilliams, Doris May, Genevieve Step\nper. Helen Herbert, Eva Edwards,\nI Lorraine E. Gerard, Mildred Dorman,\n1 Virginia Moore, Frances Moore, Myr-\nI tie Dorman, Elizabeth Bowie, Ethel\nDorman, Meiindda Fimiani, Virgie\nWilliams. Lucy Virginia Churchyard,\nAnnie May Bouchard, Josephine\nEmilio, Loretta Hausman, Dorothy\nFrazier, Frances Bitts, Angelina Sta\nsulli, Mary Stasulli, Mary Nancy\nPalano, Margaret Kennedy, Frances\nDorr, Patricia Diamond. Aileen Ham\n-1 bach and Mary Louise Stepper.\nFestivals will be held at all the\nmunicipal playgrounds from 4 p.m.\nuntil 6 p.m. The program will be\nthe same at each and will include:\n4:00 to 4:3o\u2014Boys\u2019 athletic test\n(demonstrating some of the athletics\nin which proficiency is required in\norder to he eligible for a playground\nbronze button).\nProgram for Festival.\n4:40 to s:3o\u2014May day festival; Pro\ncession, march of the May day girls,\nMaypole .dancers, flowers, etc.; fairy\ndance and awakening flowers, dance\nof the flowers. May day dance, crown\ning of the Queen, Maypole dance.\n5:30 to \u2014Girls\u2019 athletics, folk dances,\ni presentation of athletic test buttons.\nThe municipal playgrounds are:\nBloomingdale, Ist and Bryant streets\nnorthwest; Chevy Chase, 41st and\nLivingston streets northwest; Gallin\nger, F street northwest between 21st\najid -2d streets; Garfield, 2d and F\nTHE EVENING STAB. WASHINGTON. D. C.. THURSDAY, MAY 1, 1924.\nstreets southeast; Georgetown. 33d\nand Volta streets northwest; Happy\nHollow, 18th street and Kalorama\nroad northwest; Hoover, 2d street and\nDelaware avenue southwest: lowa\nAvenue, lowa avenue between Var\nnum and Webster streets northwest;\nMitchell Park, 23d and S streets\nnorthwest; Montrose Park. 30th and\nR streets northwest: New York Ave\nnue, Ist street and New York avenue\nnorthwest; Park View, Warder and\nOtis streets northwest; Plaza, 2d and\nE streogi northeast: W. R. Phillips,\nLongfell\u00dfw and Madison streets\nnorthwest; Rosedale, 17th and Kra\nmer streets northeast; Thomson. X2th\nand L streets northwest; Twin Oaks,\n14th and Taylor streets northwest;\nVan Ness, 3d and M streets southeast;\nVirginia Avenue, Virginia avenue\nsoutheast between 9th and 11th\nstreets: Cardoza, Ist and I streets\nsouthwest; Howard, sth and W\nstreets northwest; Logan. Sd and G\nstreets northeast; Payne, 15th and C\nstreets southeast: Phillips, 27th and\nO streets northwest, and Willow Tree,\n3d. 4%. B and C streets southwest.\nAt the headquarters of the Child\nWelfare Society, 2100 G northwest, a\nmaypole dance at 2 p.m. will mark\nthe opening of the playground there\nfor thd season. All children in the\ncity under six years invited.\nLENIN\nMARK SOVIET MAY 1\nBy the Associated Press.\nMOSCOW, May I.\u2014Bolshevist Rus\nsia today departed from Its usual cus\ntom of observing May day with spec\ntacular military parades, and confined\nits celebration to peaceful demonstra\ntions at the tomb of Lenin. The\nauthorities having decided to allot two\ndays to the celebration, tomorrow will\nbe given over to parades of the com\nmunistic boy scouts and children of\nthe working classes, who will take the\noath of allegiance to the revolutionary\nprinciples at Lenin\u2019s shrine.\nHundreds of thousands of workmen\nwith their families and many govern\nment employes marched from all parts\nof the city today bearing flaming ban\nners and flags and converged upon the\nmausoleum in Red square, forming a\nspectacle hardly less impressive than\nthat at the funeral of the premier.\nSpecial platoons of military police\nguarded the thoroughfares to insure\nunimpeded passage for the long col\numns of workmen and their families.\nAmbulances were stationed in the con\ngested areas to render first aid to the\ninjured. Groups of unarmed red troops\njoined the civilian processions, being\nunder orders not to organize separate\ndemonstrations.\nSpeeches were made by War Min\nister Trotsky and others, in which the\nsocialistic ideals and life work of\nLenin were the principal themes. All\ngovernment buildings, shops and homes\nwere profusely decorated with masses\nof crimson flags and streamers,, while\nRed square abounded with illuminated\nbanners, inscriptive legends, electric\nsigns and portraits of the revolution\nary leaders.\ndirectly behind Lenin\u2019s black wooden\ntomb appeared the huge red placard;\n\u201cOur banner Is Lenin. Our weapon is\nLeninism. The aim of the world is\nrevolution.\u2019\u2019\nFAREWELL DINNER\nGIVEN DR. COVELL\nDistrict Minister, Soon to Leave.;\nPraised for Welfare\nWork Here.\ni More than two hundred friends and\nadmirers of Rev. David Ransom\nCoveil gathered at a dinner in the\nCity Club last night to bid him fare- j\nwell on severing his connection with j\nTrinity Church, 3d and C streets, to\nbecome social service secretary of\nthe Episcopal diocese of Southern Cal\nifornia, with headquarters in Dos An\ngeles.\nThe esteem with which \u201cDave\u201d\nCoveil is held by thousands in Wash\nington was voiced by a dozen or more\nspeakers, including Charles F. Rob\nerts, grand master of Masons of the\nDistrict; Dr. William A. White, su\nperintendent of St. Elizabeth\u2019s Hos\npital: Brig. Gen. Amos A. Pries, chief\nof the chemical warfare service; Dr.\nLucius F. Clark, president of Ameri\ncan University: Judge Kathryn Sell\ners of the Juvenile Court and Carl\nH. Claudy.\nThe invocation was given by Rev.\nGeorge F. Dudley of St. Stephen\u2019s\nChurch. Roe Fulkerson was toast\nmaster. Dr. Conrad I'raetorius, with\nan \"hourglass\u201d timed to five minutes,\nallotted the speakers time.\nDr. White said of Dr. Covcll that\nhis work among the inmates of pris\nons, hospitals, schools for delinquent\nI boys and girls, in homes and in in\nstitutions for the mentally sick, was\nof inestimable value.\nCotnmendN Mrs. Covell.\nJudge Sellers commended Mrs. Co\nvell for her helpfulness to the. Juve\nnile Court, oftentimes presenting the\nmeans whereby young girls have been\nkept from going to training schools.\nMrs. Covell, responding, said there is\nno discrimination in creed, color, sex\nor nationality in the Juvenile Court,\nand everybody receives a square deal.\nShe said Judge Sellers is needed in\nthe court and urged everybody to\nstand back of and help her in her ef\nforts.\nGen. Pries told of methods for the\nprolongation of life and said that Dr.\nCovell\u2019s community work was in the\nforefront of such WTort. He said the\ncity so close to Hollywood needs Dr.\nCovell\u2019s help.\n\u2022Dr. Covell was presented by Roe\nFulkerson with a suit case, the gift\nof the widows and children of the\ncommunity which Dr. Covell served.\nHe also presented him with the lamb\nskin apron which he wore on the last\nMasonic Grand Dodge visitation. In\nwhich he assisted.\nCarl H. Claudy presented Dr. Covell\nwith four candles in attractive holders,\nthe gift of Harmony Lodge of Masons.\nA watch chain and knife was given to\nDr. Covell and a set of flat silver to\nMrs. Covell by Mr. Roberts on behalf\nof the Grand Lodge of Masons.\nThe toastmaster read messages of\nregret at inability to attend the dinner\nfrom Bishop James E. Freeman, J. J.\nDiamond. H. H. Sterrett, Right Rev.\nArthur S. White and others.\nAmong the guests were the mother\nand father of Dr. Covell. Mr. and Mrs.\nL. W. Covell. Mrs. B. C. Barnes, his\nsister; two brothers, Commander L. C.\nCovell of the United States coast guard\nand Maj. William E. H. Covcll, Corps\nof Engineers: Mrs. Delight R. Keller\nand Mrs. Emma A. Ransom, aunts,\nand Mr. and Mrs. John W. Stewart,\ncousins of Dr. Covell. They were all\nasked to rise. At the conclusion of\nthe festivities Rev. and Mrs. Covell\nheld a reception. The committee in\ncharge of arrangements was composed\nof Charles F. Roberts, chairman; Fred\nL. Haller, Oliver Hoyem, Harry O.\ni Kimball, Ellwood P. Morey, John J.\ni P. Mullane, Dr. Conrad Praetorlus and\nFrank T. Shull.\nCONGRESS EXPECTED\nTO ADJOURN EARLY\nHouse Could Leave Now if Sen\nate Would Finish Up\nBusiness.\nRADICALS MAY INTERFERE\nBusiness of Whole Nation Hurt by\nDelay.\nBY DAVID LAWRENCE.\nThe Whife House expects an early\nadjournment of Congress.\nThe legislative program in the\nHouse of Representatives has been\nvirtually completed and were it not\nfor the unfinished business in the\nSenate Congress could adjourn in\na week. But the delay in the Senate\nwill mean at least thirty days\u2019 more\nwork. Assuming that no filibusters\narc attempted. Congress may be able\nto adjourn in time for the national\nconventions, so that the members may\ndevote their whole time and attention\nto the presidential campaigns and the\ncongressional contests for re-election.\nThe Democrats will not block the\nRepublican plans for an early ad\njournment. They are in no mood to\nstimulate the Republicans *to work\nany harder than they care to work.\nThey are getting ready to character\nize the Republican record as a \u201cdo\nnothing\u201d session anyhow.\nBig Business Restive,\nThere are signs that the big busi\nness interests of the country want\nCongress to finish its work and go\nhome. The long delay in handling\nthe tax revision bill has not helped\nbusiness. The thought is advanced\nthat when Congress once acts on th?\ntax program and business knows ex\nactly what taxes it must pay out of\nthe incomes being earned during 1924\nmuch of the uncertainty which has\nbegun to develop in industry here\nand there will disappear. Also, the\npresent bill carries in it a flat reduc\ntion of 25 per cent on 1923 incomes\non which one quarterly installment\nalready has been made. When the\npublic knows definitely that sums al\nready laid aside for tax payments\nwill be saved, a perceptible increase\nin the buying power of the nation is\nexpected to be noted.\nFew differences between the House\nand Senate on the question of tax re\nvision have arisen, and none that can\nnot be ironed out quickly in confer\nence.\nFarm BUI Lacking.\nCongress has not adopted an agri\ncultural bill, and there are indications\nthat labor will press for passage of\nthe Howell bill, which eliminates the\npublic from the Railroad Labor Board\nand substitutes representatives of\ncapital and labor alone. The late\nPresident Harding thought the\ntrouble with the Railroad Labor\nBoard was exactly the opposite; that\nthe interested parties ought to be\neliminated and the whole board made\nup of disinterested representatives of\nthe public. Mr. Coolidge will prob.\nably share that view, though the\nchief basis for a veto, if the bill\ncomes to him for action, will be his\nobjection to the expenditure of $500,-\n000, as provided for in the proposed\nlegislation. No provision for that\nsum has been made in the budget.\nThe railroads are fighting the Howell\nbill on the ground that the present\ntransportation act has not had a\nchance to demonstrate Its value.\nA fight on railroad legislation may\nprecipitate a controversy over the\nHuman Bones Found on Coast Unsettle\nScientists' Vieivs Upon Age of Race\nAcademicians Wait Further Researches Before Re\nvising Theories About Origin of Man\u2014Fossils\nIndicate Ice Age.\nDid human beings exist on the\nPacific coast of California during the\nj later ice age, almost simultaneously\nwith the appearance of true man in\nj Europe?\nThis issue, which has caused a\nserious controversy among American i\nanthropologists and ethnologists, and\nwhich, if proved in the affirmative,\nwould upset all previous theories as to\nthe origin of the human race, was left\nopen for further research by members\nof the National Academy of Sciences,\nin session here this week, although\ngrave doubts were cast on the claims\nthat recent discoveries near Los\nAngeles represented an earlier race\nthan that which now peoples th\u00a9 earth.\nA number of these specimens were on\ndisplay and furnished one of the most\ninteresting exhibits of the convention.\nBones Declared Genuine.\nThe discoveries were explained and\nanalyzed by Dr. Chester Stock, pro-\nfessor of geology at the University of\nCalifornia, and Dr. J. C. Merriam, head\nof the Carnegie Institution bore. The\none certain conclusion was that these\ndiscoveries were not \u2022\u2019faked\u201d by some\nambitious California real estate agent\nor amateur scientist. The position of\nthe deposits indicates clearly that the\nsuggested repeal of the so-called\nguarantee clause. Investors have\nbeen worried about that possibility\nfor some time. Should Congress dis\npose of the question by failing to\nchange the transportation act, the\nholders of securities will be consider\nably cheered. This is another impor\ntant factor in the demand for an\nearly adjournment of Congress, for\nthe less the House and Senate tinker\nwith the business structure the better\nthe interested parties like it and the\nmore chance, they say, for a business\nrevival in the remainder of 1924.\nPossible Deadlock.\nThe McNary-Haugen bill will cause\na real fight. It may even delay ad\njournment. The champions of the\nmeasure are in dead earnest, and the\nopponents are insistent that no such\npiece of legislation will pass.\nThe differences are irreconcilable.\nThey represent two schools of\nthought on agricultural economics.\nThe President is preserving an atti\ntude of apparent neutrality, but his\nmessages to Congress would seem\nto be a guide to his future attitude\nand there prevails at this time con\nfidence that Tie will not sign the\nmeasure. The fact that the Norbeok\nbill was beaten is taken nowadays as\na precedent, for in that fight the\nfarm bloc was shattered. A com\nbination of southern Democrats and\neastern Republicans beat the hill. A\nsimilar alignment would kill the Mc-\nNary-Haugen bill and save the Pres\nident the problem of acting on it at\nall. Some of his friends are sure he\nwill not have to act on it. They\nwant some agricultural legislation,\nhowever, and just now the Curtis-\nAswell bill seems \u2019to have adminis\ntration favor. It would attempt to\nco-ordiqate farm co-operative or\nganizations under a federal market\ning board. There are enough things\non the calendar to delay adjournment.\nTh\u00a9 regular Democrats and Republi\ncans will not block an early ad\njournment, but maybe the radical will.\n{Copyright, 1924 J\nj ancient bones were not buried as a\nI hoax or \u201cpress agent\" stunt.\nThere is much in the surrounding\ngravel and fossil remains to indicate\nthat the these hones truly are pleisto\ncene or ice-age remnants, according\n1 to Dr. Stock. The fly in the ointment\nj is that they are similar in type to\nthose of the Channel Island Indians\nof southern California, who certainly\nare not ancient in a true sense of the\nword.\nSix Homans Discovered.\nAt least six human individuals were\nfound between the levels of 19 and\n23 feet below the surface and within\nan area of not more than 12 square\nfeet Five were adults. The sixth,\nsomewhat younger, probably was a\nwoman. The skulls might have been\ndug from a modern graveyard- They\nshow none of the primitive features\nof the Neanderthal man or his im\nmediate descendants in Europe. Dr.\nStock plans to make a large number\nof further comparisons with modern\ntypes.\nTlie denosifs. Dr. Stock concludes,\nwhile undoubtedly very ancient, can\nbe measured in thousands of years\nrather than tens of thousands. He\nI holds it possible that they may have\nbeen placed bv some prehistoric flood\nI water of tin- l>cs Angeles River, whose\nI history, previous to the present era.\ngeologists have be*n unable to de\ntermine with much exactness. The\npleistocene history of California still\nlargely is a closed book compared\nwith that of the country east of the\nRocky Mountains.\nValuable information bearing on\nthis subject is expected from the ex\ntensive trenching and building opera\ntions now in progress in the western\nsection of Dos Angeles, Dr. Stock\nsays.\nBoth Dr. Stock and Dr. Merriam\nagree that the deposits prove man\nhas existed In California for thou\nsands of years, much longer than in\nany other sections of North America\nwhere pre-Columbian human deposits\nhave been unearthed to date.\nPRESIDENT TO ATTEND.\nWill Be at Opening of Congres\nsional Country Club.\nPresident Coolidge will attend the\nofficial opening of the Congressional\nCountry Club May 23. This was an\nnounced at the White House today.\nIn addition to the President and Mrs.\nCoolidge, there will be many men\nand women of prominence in Wash\nington on hand to participate in the\nceremonies incident to this opening.\nPresident Coolidge recently was\nmade an honorary life member of the\nCongressional Country Club and at\nthe time said he hoped to be able to\ngo to the club frequently during the\ncoming season.\nTAXES DUE THIS MONTH.\nThe second half of real estate and\npersonal property taxes for the cur\nrent fiscal year is due this month.\nCollector C. M. Towers said today,\nas a reminder.\nAlthough the tax may he paid at\nany time prior to June 1, the collec\ntor advises those who can do so to\nvisit the tax office early in the month\nand avoid a last-minute rush.\nBeginning with June 1, a penalty\nof 1 per cent a month will be added\nto all bills that go unpald.\n\nSAYS LEGISLATORS\nVIOLATE DRY LAW\nBaltimore Judge Accuses Four Sen\nators and Ten Members\nof House.\nDECLINES TO NAME THEM\nAdmits He's \u201cGood Sport\" Himself.\nAdvocates Beer.\nAccusation, based on first-hand in\nformation, that four senators and ten\nmembers of Congress do \"not vote as\nthey drink\" on the prohibition ques\ntion, when made before the House ju\ndiciary committee by Judge James F.\nKiecka of the Baltimore city people's\ncourt, where he was advocating modi\nfication of the Volstead act to permit\nsale of 2.75 per cent beer, threw the\nhearing into confusion.\nUnder the avalanche of questions\nthe witness declined to give any\nnames and his testimony was there\nfore stricken from the record, but not\nbefore he had stated in reply to a\nquestion that he himself has spent a\nlarge sum of money in Washington\nentertaining members of Congress,\ndiplomats and others. He explained\nthat he was \u201ca good sport as- well as\na judge.\" but this phase of the exam\nination was not developed in detail.\nSays Driest l ike Liquor.\nJudge Kleeka asserted that some of\nthe \"driest\u201d members of Congress\n\u201crelish their liquor,\u201d and thnt before\nthe recent investigations started in\nWashington drinks could be obtained\nin both the Senate and House office\nbuildings.\n\u201cFine old Kentucky liquor,\u201d he add\ned, was the brand offered by \u201ccertain\"\nHouse members.\nKiecka said he had been on \u201cnumer\nous hunting trips and parties\" with\nmembers of Congress, and that his in\nformation was \u201cfirst-hand.\"\nBesides Kiecka, numerous other wit\nnesses appeared before the committee,\nwhich today concluded the taking of\ntestimony from advocates of modifica\ntion. Although several House mem\nbers desire to be heard on the side of\nmodification, it is expected that oppo\nnents, under the leadership of Wayne\nB. Wheeler, general counsel of the\nAnti-Saloon League, first will present\ntheir arguments.\nWIFE ACCUSED IN SUIT.\nJohn Donnelly Charges Attempt on\nLife With Knife.\nJohn Donnelly, 1201 N street has\nfiled suit in the District Supreme\n1 Court for an absolute divorce from\nHelen Donnelly. The wife recently\ni sued her husband for maintenance.\nDonnolly charges cruelty and miscon\nduct and asserts that his wife once\nattempted his life by assaulting him\nwith a carving knife. She usetl house\nhold money to entertain other men.\nhe declares. Attorneys Frank K.\nElder and Lucien H. Vandoren rep\nresent the husband.\nJames A. Barr, 1222 Connecticut\navenue has asked for an absolute, di\nvorce from his wife, Dorothy M. Barr.\nThey were married March 14, 191 k\nand have one child. The husband\ntells the court his wife and the al\nleged co-respondent were recently ar\nrested in Arlington County, Va., and\nfined on a joint statutory charge. At\ntorney E. D. Detwiler appears for the\n.husband.\n17","height":"24984","width":"19404"}}
